WEBVTT

00:08.880 --> 00:13.000
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:30.000 --> 00:35.120
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

00:38.120 --> 00:39.700
And here are your hosts.

00:44.240 --> 00:52.860
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. For 20 years, Roger Zelazny has been
writing science fiction and fantasy. He tells us why and how he became a science

00:52.860 --> 00:59.320
fiction writer. Well, it's a funny thing. I was

00:59.320 --> 01:08.760
originally a reader of science fiction from about the age of 11 on through high
school. And during that period, I did write a lot of science fiction stories,

01:08.800 --> 01:23.140
which I tried to sell, but I was like in my early teens. And I didn't really
meet with any success at that point. And I decided, actually before that, that

01:23.140 --> 01:32.860
I'd wanted to be a writer. I wasn't, it wasn't necessarily science fiction that
I had in mind, though. It was science fiction stories that I was writing during

01:32.860 --> 01:40.480
the period I was reading them. When I went to college, I stopped reading science
fiction, just to concentrate on the material I had there. And I wrote poetry,

01:40.500 --> 01:50.900
actually, exclusively. I decided that I was going to start writing again as soon
as I got out of college and had some time. And at that point, I wasn't

01:50.900 --> 02:06.960
absolutely certain what it was that I would try writing. But when the
opportunity finally presented itself in early 1962, I decided it might be easier

02:06.960 --> 02:17.740
for me to break into science fiction since I had read so much of it in the past.
I knew the area, so I decided I'd try there first. And I went out and re

02:17.740 --> 02:29.140
-familiarized myself with science fiction. And then I began writing and
submitting the stories. And after about six or seven weeks, I sold my first one.

02:30.820 --> 02:42.100
And I sold 16 others that year, so I stayed with it. Zelazny has always been
recognized as a stylist, a writer to whom craftsmanship is important. His

02:42.100 --> 02:49.880
characters have depth, and his prose is coherent and flexible. Right. And that's
an important point to make. Science fiction has traditionally been a field in

02:49.880 --> 02:57.820
which style and character were secondary to plot and idea. Zelazny's college
background in his major field of study, English, may have had some influence on

02:57.820 --> 03:10.160
his writing. As an undergraduate, I was a psychology major. And I decided I did
not really want to work as a psychologist. And it occurred to me somewhere along

03:10.160 --> 03:21.580
the line that if I were simply going to be teaching and writing with the aim in
mind of eventually writing full time, I might as well teach something that would

03:21.580 --> 03:32.540
be a little more fun than psychology. So I switched to English and took my
graduate work in English and comparative literature. As a result of this

03:32.540 --> 03:43.180
background, Zelazny says, his stories had some characteristics not common to
traditional science fiction. I suppose having grown up on the earlier sort of

03:43.180 --> 03:55.420
science fiction, the space opera sort of thing of the 30s and 40s too, and the
harder science stories of the 40s and some of the sociological science fiction

03:55.420 --> 04:10.740
of the 50s, and having a background in literature, there's a natural tendency,
whether it's conscious or not, to want to do something different than things

04:10.740 --> 04:21.420
that had gone before. As a consequence, my stories, well, the first ones were
basically gimmick stories because it was the easiest way to break in. It was

04:21.420 --> 04:30.660
about all that I was capable of doing at the time. But when I began writing at
greater length and when I was a bit sure of myself, I would think of the

04:30.660 --> 04:39.740
characters first, so the stories tended to have more, I suppose, in the way of
psychological motivation rather than just external characterization.

04:42.120 --> 05:00.480
And my writing itself, possibly because of the years I'd spent writing poetry
and reading general literature, tended to be a bit different from some of the

05:00.480 --> 05:06.900
earlier things which were kind of journalistic in character. More next time
about Roger Zelazny.

05:14.420 --> 05:22.620
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

05:22.620 --> 05:29.260
Odessa, Texas. 

