05:53.020 --> 05:53.380


06:09.260 --> 06:13.320
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:29.740 --> 06:35.200
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

06:38.060 --> 06:39.760
And here are your hosts.

06:44.040 --> 06:52.040
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. Science fiction authors sometimes write
fantasy, and fantasy authors sometimes write science fiction. Roger Zelazny

06:52.040 --> 07:02.780
writes both. He talks about the differences between the two forms. I do make the
distinction myself. I mean, in a science fiction story, everything, I feel,

07:03.580 --> 07:16.900
should be explainable in terms of natural laws or extensions of natural laws as
we understand them now. Whereas in a fantasy story, it's part of the rules of

07:16.900 --> 07:25.540
the game, so I feel there are no compunctions against invoking the supernatural
or bringing in magic and things of that sort.

07:28.280 --> 07:39.180
And so basically a science fiction story, things are ultimately explainable in a
fantasy story. They're explainable really in terms of something that isn't

07:39.180 --> 07:44.380
explainable. So you've got more of the... You've got the...

07:46.440 --> 07:58.460
The less rational background if you push things far enough in a fantasy story.
Zelazny says he writes some of his books so that they can be read either way. I

07:58.460 --> 08:01.500
also believe in mixing the two.

08:05.000 --> 08:17.100
Well, Lord of Light, for instance, was a book which... Where I intentionally
wrote it to be taken two ways. A fantasy fan could read it as a piece of

08:17.100 --> 08:29.040
fantasy. Whereas a science fiction fan also had options available to him. Any
single item which occurs in there, which is of an unusual nature, is that

08:29.040 --> 08:39.000
there's ultimately an explanation available for it if the person cares to use
it. If he doesn't, that's fine too. Zelazny makes an interesting point about

08:39.000 --> 08:46.460
science fiction. He says that sometimes a science fiction story will become a
fantasy story after a certain amount of time. And he uses one of his own

08:46.460 --> 08:59.600
stories, A Rose for Ecclesiastes, as an example. It's kind of funny too because
I think the first story for which I became known was a piece called A Rose for

08:59.600 --> 09:00.400
Ecclesiastes.

09:05.400 --> 09:18.580
And one of my reasons in writing this is because I was very fond of the earlier
space operas and things like this where they played John Carter of Mars. And I

09:18.580 --> 09:30.920
had always wanted to do something set on the Mars which existed in these earlier
stories. And I knew at the time I wrote it that it was scientifically impossible

09:30.920 --> 09:39.960
at that point. We already knew enough about Mars to know that the temperature
was not the same as I had it in the story, that the atmosphere was not the same

09:39.960 --> 09:49.620
and so forth. But it was close enough to the point where this knowledge was just
becoming current that I could still get away with doing a thing like that. So I

09:49.620 --> 10:04.140
intentionally wrote that and wrote it in the fashion I did. It was a kind of
exercise in nostalgia on my part. I'd always wanted to do a story set on that

10:04.140 --> 10:14.100
kind of Mars. And I knew that if I waited another year or so I wouldn't be able
to. The same with Venus for my story, The Doors of His Face, The Lamps of His

10:14.100 --> 10:23.980
Mouth. At that point we already were aware that the surface temperature was
about 900 degrees. But still there were these, there was this whole traditional

10:23.980 --> 10:38.000
body of science fiction literature which had a vast watery world, misty and so
forth, that I really had wanted to use at least once in my life. So I did those

10:38.000 --> 10:52.040
two stories as a kind of tribute to the earlier things. But then again I wrote
them the way I was writing then rather than in the older style. So reading them

10:52.040 --> 11:02.600
now they'd have to be regarded as fantasy rather than science fiction because
science has already demonstrated that those circumstances don't prevail. More on

11:02.600 --> 11:03.620
Roger Zelazny tomorrow.

11:11.420 --> 11:19.660
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

11:19.660 --> 11:30.380
Odessa, Texas. 

