12:01.860 --> 12:05.900
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

12:22.280 --> 12:27.640
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

12:30.500 --> 12:32.140
And here are your hosts.

12:36.360 --> 12:45.020
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. Many science fiction and fantasy authors
these days write novels in series, in three, four, and sometimes five book sets.

12:45.020 --> 12:52.960
Jack Chalker's Well World series, or Elizabeth Lynn's trilogy, The Chronicles of
Tornor, are two good examples. It's a commercially attractive idea, for one

12:52.960 --> 13:00.320
thing. If readers like the first book, then there's a ready-made market for the
following ones. And, of course, it also allows an author the scope to pursue a

13:00.320 --> 13:08.240
theme in greater depth and length than a single book would allow. And the extra
depth can give an epic quality to the series. One of the best of the series is a

13:08.240 --> 13:17.260
set of five books by Roger Zelazny, a science fantasy adventure called, simply,
The Amber Series. The first volume is entitled, Nine Princes in Amber, and it

13:17.260 --> 13:27.620
was published in 1971. The other four, The Guns of Avalon, Sign of the Unicorn,
The Hand of Oberon, and The Courts of Chaos. Zelazny calls the book something

13:27.620 --> 13:36.720
besides science fantasy. Whenever I try anything of this sort, I try to give it
an extra twist, is what it is. Basically, I look at it myself as a kind of

13:36.720 --> 13:49.080
heroic fantasy, with a few variations that don't usually occur in that sort of
literature. One of the variations Zelazny develops in the books is what's called

13:49.080 --> 14:07.440
the pattern. It is a kind of archetypal design which exists in the real world,
amber, of which our own earth and a great variety of shadings and variations

14:07.440 --> 14:25.000
thereof exist. Amber is the real world, and the others are referred to as
shadow, our shadow in the stories. The background, the basis of reality in amber

14:25.000 --> 14:34.280
is this design called the pattern, which was inscribed by an ancestor of the
clan,

14:36.100 --> 14:49.540
about whom the story is told. Only a person of the blood of the royal family of
amber is able to walk this pattern and not be destroyed by it. And in the course

14:49.540 --> 15:05.860
of walking the pattern, at some point in his early life, the amberite acquires
the ability to walk through the various shadow worlds. which surround amber, so

15:05.860 --> 15:16.200
that he can travel through an infinity of possibilities to virtually any world
he desires. The basic plot of the series consists of a struggle for the throne

15:16.200 --> 15:24.460
of amber, and in the process, our earth is threatened with destruction, since
we're only a shadow of the real world of amber. In the struggle, the main

15:24.460 --> 15:32.480
character, Corwin, keeps traveling between our earth and amber. Technology
doesn't work in amber, so the people there fight with swords and magic. For this

15:32.480 --> 15:41.140
reason, the books are called science fantasy, or as Zelazny said, heroic
fantasy. They've been very popular, too. Zelazny says the readers have responded

15:41.140 --> 15:51.120
enthusiastically. I have gotten more fan letters on the amber books than
anything else I've ever written. There was a period of a couple years there

15:51.120 --> 15:59.740
where I was getting several letters a week on the amber books. The narrative was
concluded with an exciting climax in the fifth book, The Courts of Chaos.

16:00.160 --> 16:07.080
Because of the wide reader response, though, and because there were some
unanswered questions in that last book, a sixth novel on amber is a possibility.

16:08.200 --> 16:18.800
There is possibly a sixth one. I have made no commitments. I do not have a plot.
But I've been talking about it and thinking about it, publisher.

16:21.520 --> 16:32.840
And it is possible when I get a few things out of the way that I'm writing now
that I might go on and do a sixth one. But so far as the five books that now

16:32.840 --> 16:44.320
exist are concerned, that story is told. That was the story I had in mind.
Anything which would continue, the series would probably take off in a new

16:44.320 --> 16:50.180
direction. It could possibly be from another character's point of view. More
about Roger Zelazny next time.

