18:18.620 --> 18:20.220
And here are your hosts.

18:24.380 --> 18:32.340
This is Daryl Lane. And David Carson. One of the more interesting time travel
books in recent years is Roadmarks by Roger Zelazny. Though time travel is one

18:32.340 --> 18:42.880
of the traditional science fiction themes, Zelazny doesn't often write that type
of story. I have always attempted to avoid time travel stories because I don't

18:42.880 --> 18:56.960
like the paradoxes involved. In fact, the only thing I can think of that I had
done in the past was a short story called Divine Madness. I said that I really

18:56.960 --> 19:00.820
wouldn't write a time travel story unless I came up with a new gimmick.

19:05.180 --> 19:20.160
Well, for Roadmarks, I thought I had something just in the image of time
considered as a superhighway, basically, and withouts for the paradoxes in the

19:20.160 --> 19:36.240
Everett Wheeler parallel world sort of situation. And it was really the image of
the road that fascinated me and led to my writing that particular book. Time is

19:36.240 --> 19:43.940
conceived as a superhighway in Roadmarks, with the exits leading to different
eras throughout time. Zelazny has an interesting story to tell regarding the

19:43.940 --> 19:58.920
origin of the idea behind Roadmarks. I got the idea for that book here in New
Mexico, really. One Sunday I was just out for a drive on I-25, which is a nice

19:58.920 --> 20:01.940
highway

20:01.940 --> 20:14.320
-type road. I took a turn off and drove for a few minutes, and the road rapidly
degenerated until, within a matter of minutes, I was on a dirt road, and I

20:14.320 --> 20:26.720
passed through a place that I couldn't even find on the map. It was a little
village where there was a horse pulling a wagon and no overhead electrical lines

20:26.720 --> 20:39.880
in sight. It was almost as if I had driven back through time into the 19th
century. There were log buildings, and somewhere

20:39.880 --> 20:47.640
around there something started to click, and as I drove back again, the road
improved and improved until finally I was on the superhighway. I started working

20:47.640 --> 21:00.880
out just the mechanisms for the idea of driving through time, which I used in
Roadmarks. Actually, by the time I got home, I had a number of the situations

21:00.880 --> 21:04.060
worked out, and I sat down and began writing it.

21:10.800 --> 21:18.700
The protagonist is a man named Red Dorakeen. He travels up and down this highway
of time in a battered old pickup. And when he's not trying to avoid and outwit

21:18.700 --> 21:25.740
some assassins who are after him, he's running guns to the Greeks back in the
past at Marathon. And there's something else in the book that's a recurring

21:25.740 --> 21:33.780
motif or symbol. Huge dragons that float above the road occasionally. Their
function is not clear, but they seem to have some responsibility for the road.

21:34.040 --> 21:48.460
Oh, they were simply to represent the dark forces, which I tend to bring in any
fantasy novel. In a story like this, there has to be a point where you have to

21:48.460 --> 22:00.780
ultimately reach something that's basically unexplainable. Namely, where did the
road come from and how did it come to function the way that it did? And in

22:00.780 --> 22:12.480
making a decision on that, I could go either way. I could find some science
fiction trappings and explain it, or I could leave it intentionally something

22:12.480 --> 22:24.060
shadowy and with a more fantasy background. If I did that, I'd decide I needed
some symbol to invoke as an ultimate creator of the road, so hence the dragons

22:24.060 --> 22:33.280
and then their tie in with red. Roadmarks, published in 1981, is a different
sort of time travel story, tending toward the fantasy rather than the science

22:33.280 --> 22:41.160
fiction end of the spectrum. And since Roger Zelazny is responsible for it, it's
highly enjoyable. And we'll have more on Roger Zelazny on our next show.

22:48.620 --> 22:56.620
