24:10.260 --> 24:11.800
And here are your hosts.

24:16.100 --> 24:23.720
This is Daryl Lane. And David Carson. Writer Roger Zelazny has won numerous
awards in the field of science fiction and fantasy, and he's been writing it for

24:23.720 --> 24:31.720
some 20 years. So, Zelazny has a scholarly background which often shows up in his
books, the way he uses mythology, for instance, in novels like Lord of Light or

24:31.720 --> 24:40.260
This Immortal, or psychology and The Dream Masters. He has a master's degree in
literature, and his knowledge of history is extensive. He's read deeply in the

24:40.260 --> 24:47.880
mythologies and early literature of mankind, and he also reads a great deal of
modern literature, both science fiction and otherwise. He has some interesting

24:47.880 --> 24:57.300
ideas on science fiction and fantasy and its place in the modern world. Science
fiction is a special genre to him for a few basic reasons. It is, for one

24:57.300 --> 25:06.460
reason, one of the few special places where you still deal with characters

25:07.640 --> 25:20.500
other than those which occur in the modern realistic or naturalistic novel.
Going back to the critic Northrop Frye, who spoke of broke characters into

25:20.500 --> 25:32.060
various modes, science fiction is one of the few places outside of, say, modern
poetry, where a writer can deal with characters in what he called the high

25:32.060 --> 25:41.680
mimetic or the mythic modes, that is, characters who are greater than their
fellow man, or characters who are godlike sometimes. Sometimes in that science

25:41.680 --> 25:52.460
fiction does deal with mutants and aliens and sentient computers and cyborgs and
robots, what have you, just whole categories of beings which are different than

25:52.460 --> 26:01.220
the characters you meet with in a naturalistic or realistic novel. So in that
sense, and I think this is one of the great virtues of science fiction, it gives

26:01.220 --> 26:04.640
the writer more scope for exploration in terms of character.

26:16.080 --> 26:24.060
Besides the freedom or scope that science fiction provides for a writer, it also
has one other quality that Zelazny feels differentiates it from general or

26:24.060 --> 26:36.800
mainstream literature. I think that science fiction is still, basically for all
of the experimentation that went on in the 60s, a bastion of storytelling. The

26:36.800 --> 26:47.280
idea is not necessarily the hero anymore, as it was in the days Kingsley Amos
referred to it as being such back in the 40s, and perhaps the 50s, but we have

26:47.280 --> 26:57.860
real characters now, and ideas are handled in a more sophisticated fashion. The
writing has also improved from a stylistic standpoint, but basically I think if

26:57.860 --> 27:10.300
you looked at the area, well, even statistically, there are more examples of
straightforward storytelling in science fiction than you might find in general

27:10.300 --> 27:21.580
fiction at large. So that is another reason I am very fond of science fiction
because I am basically a storyteller no matter what I do with mythology or

27:21.580 --> 27:32.900
writing devices. Does Zelazny think science fiction will ever merge with general
literature and gain a wider acceptance? I don't think it will necessarily be

27:32.900 --> 27:46.520
merged with the mainstream, and I also do not think that this is necessarily a
bad thing at all. It was Santayana who said about something else entirely, but

27:46.520 --> 27:58.420
which I think is apropos, that to attempt to give such things a wide currency is
to be willing to denature them in order to boast that they've been propagated. I

27:58.420 --> 28:10.840
think science fiction will always have its devotees in that they will grow in
number just as the population itself increases, but I don't know that the

28:10.840 --> 28:19.280
percentage is ever going to increase that greatly. The chances are pretty good
that science fiction has at least a few more readers and fans than it would have

28:19.280 --> 28:25.420
had had Zelazny not taken it up. His works stand as an advertisement for the
quality and value of good science fiction.

